    <a title="Heather" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2615211-heather"><img alt="Heather" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1265909675p2/2615211.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/69354859?book_show_action=true">Aug 29, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Heather" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Heather" href="/user/show/2615211-heather">Heather</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2615211-heather?shelf=great-fiction">great-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer69354859" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14036186469181094060">This story about 4 women trapped inside a car during a blizzard, sharing stories about their dead ex-husband, has all the things I love in it about Louise Erdrich: the fantastic and the strange, the beautiful and the everyday, all mingled together in that overcrowded car. Plus, it manages to answer a few unresolved questions about some of her other novel&apos;s characters, too. But, as others have said in their reviews, not Erdrich&apos;s best work, and so not a great representation of her work. For that,</span>
  <span id="freeText14036186469181094060" style="display:none">This story about 4 women trapped inside a car during a blizzard, sharing stories about their dead ex-husband, has all the things I love in it about Louise Erdrich: the fantastic and the strange, the beautiful and the everyday, all mingled together in that overcrowded car. Plus, it manages to answer a few unresolved questions about some of her other novel's characters, too. But, as others have said in their reviews, not Erdrich's best work, and so not a great representation of her work. For that, try Tracks or The Master Butcher's Singing Club.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14036186469181094060" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
