    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3376330671" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3376330671" />
    <a title="Sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5914286-sarah"><img alt="Sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1317863882p2/5914286.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3376330671?book_show_action=true">Jun 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah" href="/user/show/5914286-sarah">Sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3376330671" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7110515313650244806">Another look at the people and history surrounding her fictional Argus North Dakota. I enjoyed hanging out with these folks again. It almost veered into magical realism, so many extreme coincidences that I almost didn&apos;t believe it. The tragedy of June&apos;s death is the driver of everything in this novel (just as in Love Medicine). One very damaged man who marries 5 women - and in some way deeply cares for each of them. Essentially his selfishness screws up every relationship, and every thing in his</span>
  <span id="freeText7110515313650244806" style="display:none">Another look at the people and history surrounding her fictional Argus North Dakota. I enjoyed hanging out with these folks again. It almost veered into magical realism, so many extreme coincidences that I almost didn't believe it. The tragedy of June's death is the driver of everything in this novel (just as in Love Medicine). One very damaged man who marries 5 women - and in some way deeply cares for each of them. Essentially his selfishness screws up every relationship, and every thing in his life. How could I enjoy reading this? Its sound like misery upon misery, but its not. Somehow, each character (and there are a lot, this is a long book), makes it out as a slightly better person, and a person who is more sure and comfortable with the love they have, and the love they have to give. I'm not entirely sure this book needed to be as long as it is; it may have been better if shorter. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7110515313650244806" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


